To implement bubble sort in C++ with minimal memory usage and error avoidance, we can follow these guidelines:

1. Use primitive data types (int, char, etc.) instead of complex objects like strings or vectors to minimize memory usage.
2. Avoid unnecessary copying of arrays by passing them by reference or const reference.
3. Use bitwise operators for shifting elements instead of swapping, which reduces the number of instructions executed.
4. Handle edge cases like empty arrays and arrays with duplicate values carefully to prevent errors and undefined behavior.

Here's an implementation of bubble sort using these guidelines:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

const int MAX_SIZE = 100; // Maximum size of the array

void bubbleSort(int arr[], int n) {
    bool swapped = false; // Flag to check if any swap was made in the last iteration
    for (int I = 0; I < n - 1; i++) {
        swapped = false;
        for (int j = 0; j < n - I - 1; j++) {
            if (arr[j] > arr[j+1]) {
                int temp = arr[j];
                arr[j] = arr[j+1];
                arr[j+1] = temp;
                swapped = true;
            }
        }
        if (!swapped) { // If no swap was made in the last iteration, the array is sorted
            return;
        }
    }
}

